1. The Role of Continuous Compliance

Continuous compliance means ensuring your systems remain compliant with policies (e.g., NIST SP 800-53) at all times through:

    Automated validation: Regular testing to ensure policies are correctly implemented and enforced.
    Visibility: Providing clear, actionable insights into compliance status.
    Resilience: Rapidly identifying and addressing violations or misconfigurations.


InSpec doesn’t enforce policies in real time—it’s primarily a testing tool. The real-time enforcement happens through the OPA engine.

3. How Often Should InSpec Run?

The frequency of InSpec tests depends on the nature of your system and compliance requirements. Here are some scenarios:
Real-Time Systems or Critical Workloads

    Frequency: Run InSpec tests every few minutes (e.g., 1-5 min intervals).
    Why: Critical systems may need near-real-time validation to ensure compliance and detect violations quickly.
    How: Automate InSpec tests with a scheduler (e.g., cron jobs, CI/CD pipelines).

Moderate Workloads

    Frequency: Run tests hourly.
    Why: For workloads that don’t have constant changes, hourly checks are often sufficient to detect issues early.

Low-Change Environments

    Frequency: Run daily or after configuration changes.
    Why: If the system configuration rarely changes, frequent checks may not add much value.



